<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Star Wars TCG</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Women and Gaming...Oil and Water, or Rum and Coke?<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.64)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1906'>Heidi-Marie "Dalantyr" Farinholt</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=1906&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> June 3, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Women and gaming...oil and water, or rum and coke?<br>
<br>
For those of you that read the original article that I wrote three years ago, this is the results of three years of thinking, banging my head against the wall, and some occasional licentious alcohol consumption (For reference, the original article was &quot;On Women and SWCCG&quot; and still lives in the DeckTech archives...somewhere...)<br>
<br>
Okay, okay, so we all figured out at some time in some sandbox that little girls and little boys are different.  How different is the study of a lifetime, and should not be undertaken unless you have a nice quiet place with nothing else to do but consume beer and pretzels (say, a monastery, but then again you&#39;d get flogged for thinking about girls...).  Beyond the physical differences (which again, are more obvious in particular representatives of the species than in others), there&#39;s a great deal of psychological differences, and no, I&#39;m not referring to the ones that come along every twenty-eight days or so.<br>
<br>
It all starts just a few years beyond the sandbox.  (I&#39;m leaving out the period of time before that, because in all reality, during that time, the identity of gender is defined by your mom&#39;s taste in clothing.)  At some point, maybe having to do with some strange hormonal thing, girls and boys start to worry about what the other gender thinks about them.  Girls try to dress-up, and boys start spending hours in the bathroom looking for that one first facial fuzzling that makes them &quot;a man&quot;.  In PE class, girls talk in the locker room about who&#39;s wearing bras, while boys look down at their shorts wondering when they&#39;ll grow out of their Youth-size jock strap.  Puberty&#39;s happening here, and hormones are in the air (quite literally).  Sex is no longer something you dread walking in on in your parents&#39; bedroom.  Deodorant becomes a must.  Girls discover the neverending hell of having to shave their legs.  Guys find that having facial hair is a real pain (literally) and thus start trying to grow beards but really only end up with what looks like a denuded Brillo pad.<br>
<br>
Girls get brainwashed at some point during this period and start thinking that guys will only like them if they are pretty and dainty and lose the necessity for certain very necessary bodily functions.  Now a lot of girls fall into this mold.  However, as in any social structure, there are always the nonconformists.  The &quot;weird&quot;, &quot;dorky&quot; girls that scuff around in jeans and a sweater instead of the latest capris and babydoll shirts, minding their own business and oftentimes being bothered by their more-trendy and less-mindly anatomical similars.  (Let me just say that being the cause of annoyance to the social elite is quite a bit of fun.  I personally wore mismatched socks deliberately for a good part of high school just because it drove a particular clique up the wall.)  Now some of these &quot;less-desirables&quot; end up getting assimilated into the larger flock, but a few manage to keep their identity and position as outriders.  The Collective (you can figure out what I&#39;m talking about) tries to convince these outriders that they are ugly, stupid, aren’t going to amount to anything, etc... out of one thing:  FEAR.  Because what they know, on some primal, instinctive level that they can&#39;t identify, is that a few years down the road, these outriders of the social slimetrail are going to be very sought-after in a few short years, for that very individuality that they so despise.<br>
<br>
It&#39;s no great elemental secret that the proportion of males to females among the gaming community is astronomical.  DeckTech is a perfect example – for the THOUSANDS of male members, there are at most only fifty women registered.  Of those fifty, up until recently only two were active posters.  That puts a female in an interesting position (do NOT read too much into that).  The women that you&#39;re going to find on DeckTech aren&#39;t going to be the part of that high-school Collective.  You&#39;re going to find those outriders, each very individual, in that refined form that Buffy and Muffy were so worried about.  They&#39;re not morons, either.  The three most well-known gamer chicks (at least in the DeckTech community) are a child psychologist, a marketing project manager, and a medical student.  (Two are single...the marketing PM is married to, of all things, a gaming guy)<br>
<br>
Now, what is a secret is that guess what, guys:  being a gamer girl does not mean that you&#39;re surrounded by possible boyfriends.  Quite the contrary, actually.  While admittedly some guys like sharing the game with their girlfriend, others don&#39;t, preferring to keep that &quot;in the closet&quot;.  (Interesting that an interest in gaming as well as sexual preference end up in there)  That widely opens up the realm of possible females.  The guys that DO want to share the game with their girlfriends are more limited in choices due to the limited numbers of gamer chicks, and thus their numbers are decreased as well.  But what often gets overlooked is that gamer girls have an equally different problem in finding guys that don&#39;t mind them playing!  Unless you&#39;re willing to go trolling in comic stores, it&#39;s very difficult to find a guy that doesn&#39;t look at you sideways when you mention that you like to play games on your PlayStation (and don&#39;t even THINK about mentioning the original functioning NES that lives in your closet).  I&#39;ll say that more than once (and NO, I will not quote a specific number) I&#39;ve run into that particular hurdle.  It&#39;s a real first- or second-date killer :P<br>
<br>
Okay, so when you finally find that great, successful woman that totally blows your mind when she beats you at site 4 with her LOTR deck (and, by the way, is completely naked while doing so), how do you keep her from getting away from you?  This is the million-dollar question, isn&#39;t it?<br>
<br>
Remember that while girls may play games, they don&#39;t play games the same way that guys do.  Girls put a LOT of themselves into everything that they do, creating a much greater level of emotional output.  Using your girlfriend as a beating post for your own ego is NOT the way to keep her playing the game.  I&#39;ve heard a couple of horror stories of girls completely turned off of playing CCG&#39;s as a result of being treated like punching bags (they&#39;re currently in Pokemon therapy).  Sometimes girls just need to win a game.  Sorry guys, but this is how it is.  Be nice to your girlfriend and she will be nice to you (and how nice depends on how old she is and what is legal in your state).  Girls tend to get pissed about little things more easily (I can hear the chorus of &quot;no shimmer&quot; from here)...as a result of this higher level of emotional attachment.  Sometimes all she needs after a hard game or a bad day is a no-strings-attached bear hug.  Don&#39;t ask her what she did wrong, don&#39;t grill her about how she should have tracked that Operational as Planned to kill Ben Kenobi for the whole trip home from the tournament.  Ice cream also works well, but may be controversial :)  Keeping a good gaming partner is much like maintaining the rest of the relationship – a little give-and-take, often fun, and occasionally a pain in the tail to deal with.  It doesn&#39;t work for all couples, but there are also some great success stories.  A great couple lives up in the DC area, both are avid computer gamers, the husband plays CCG&#39;s.  When he was playing in the State Championships last year his wife was there helping run command cards and rulings.  So it can be done.<br>
<br>
The whole point of this article (and perhaps I have danced around it more than a worm dangling above the vat of tequila) is to give the gaming community a look at relationships and gaming attitude from the viewpoint of ONE female.  Undoubtedly others by nature of their individuality are going to have different opinions.  Opinions are like almost every other part of the human anatomy...everyone has one.  <br>
<br>
I&#39;ll leave you with a joke:<br>
A young man sidles up to a woman at a bar and asks, &quot;What do you do?&quot;<br>
&quot;I’m a doctor,&quot; she says.<br>
&quot;I wish I could be ill and let you doctor me,&quot; he whispers in her ear.<br>
&quot;Be careful what you wish for,&quot; she replies.  &quot;I’m a proctologist.&quot;<br>
